eakup of the old New Deal coalition; introduces the most important difference between our current era and past eras, the rise of "negative partisanship"; explains how this phenomenon paved the way for the Trump presidency; and examines why our polarization could even grow deeper. This statistically based analysis shows that racial anxiety is by far a better predictor of support for Donald Trump than any other factor, including economic discontent.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Nov 2019) 0aPolitical partieszUnited Statesy20th century. 0aPolitical partieszUnited Statesy21st century. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / American Government / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYUP eBook Package 2018z978311063899840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780300235128423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780300235128.jpg  a978-3-11-063899-8  YUP eBook Package 2018b2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles